FBIS3-27933 "dreas021__a94006" FBIS-EAS-94-021-A Document Type:Daily Report 1 February 1994 ANNEX Japan * MOF Study on Foreign Direct Investment, Trade 942A0048A Tokyo FINANCE in Japanese Sep, Oct 93--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY 942A0048A Tokyo FINANCE Language: Japanese Article Type:CSO [Article by Ministry of Finance Customs Bureau staff: "Changes in Japan's Trade Structure and Foreign Direct Investments"] [Sep 93 pp 21-28] [Text] Foreign direct investments have played an increasingly important role in the international economy since the latter half of the 1980's. While world trade grew steadily at an annual rate of 13 percent from 1985 to 1990, foreign direct investments, showing even greater growth, expanded at an annual rate of 34 percent. In the midst of these changes in the world economy, we see the rapid growth of Japanese foreign direct investments since the Plaza Accord of 1985 as well as changes in Japan's trade structure. In view of these changes, the International Research Section of the Ministry of Finance [MOF] Customs and Tariff Bureau conducted a survey over a one-year period to address the following and other questions: 1) how has the expansion of foreign direct investments changed Japan's trade structure; 2) what kinds of changes have occurred with respect to Japan's international air cargo industry along with these other changes; and 3) what is the status of attempts by Japanese enterprises, which underlie these changes in the trade structure, to localize production? Here and in the following (October) issue, we would like to introduce findings from this survey regarding changes in Japan's trade structure from the latter half of the 1980's through 1992. I. Introduction During the latter half of the 1980's, Japan's trade structure underwent dynamic changes both in terms of imports and exports. Using figures indicating the volume of trade in terms of quantity [e.g., number of cars exported] rather than in just dollar amounts, which is a less accurate measure of volume, we see that during the first half of the 1980's (specifically, in 1980, 1981 and 1984), with the yen still weak, exports grew at a two-digit rate. That changed to a single-digit, however, from 1987. In 1992, the rate of growth in exports had fallen to 0.2 percent due to the J-curve effect following the yen's appreciation and to more higher value added export items (Tables 1 and 2). For example, in the case of automobiles, which were Japan's leading export through the 1980's, making up almost 20 percent of all Japanese exports during that period, exports, as measured in dollars, continued to grow while the actual number of cars shipped from Japan fell (from 7.01 million cars in 1986 to 6 million in 1992), indicating that the growth in exports was due to price factors rather than to a change in the number of cars being exported. Again, along with a growth in foreign direct investments by Japan's enterprises, growth in export parts (for example, semiconductor and electronic parts, car parts and engines), which were hard to secure in the countries where Japanese enterprises had set up their branch operations, became a characteristic of the export trade during the latter half of the 1980's (Table 3). Table 1. Changes in Export/Import Prices (Based on the Dollar), Quantitative Growth Rate, and Exchange Rate (Units: percent change, yen/dollar) Exports Imports Exchange Rate Calendar [Dollar] Price Quantity [Dollar] Price Quantity (Yen/Dollar) Rate of Year Amount Amount Appreciation 1980 26.0 7.1 17.7 27.0 30.9 -3.0 226.4 -3.5 1981 17.1 6.0 10.5 2.0 3.4 -1.4 220.2 2.7 1982 -8.7 -6.6 -2.2 -7.9 -7.3 -0.6 248.0 -12.7 1983 5.8 -1.9 7.9 -4.2 -5.0 0.8 237.6 4.2 1984 15.8 0.3 16.2 8.0 2.3 10.5 237.1 0.2 1985 3.2 -1.3 4.6 -5.1 -5.5 0.4 238.9 -0.8 1986 19.1 19.8 -0.6 -2.4 -10.9 9.5 168.7 29.4 1987 9.6 9.3 0.3 18.3 8.1 9.3 145.3 13.9 1988 15.6 10.0 5.1 25.3 7.5 16.7 128.1 11.9 1989 3.9 -0.1 3.8 12.5 4.3 7.8 137.5 -7.3 1990 4.3 -1.1 5.5 11.4 5.3 5.8 144.5 -5.1 1991 9.6 