s in steel and nonferrous metals (aluminum, aluminum alloys, copper and copper alloys), the result of the bubble economy's collapse and the domestic economy's entering an adjustment phase. Where local production by Japanese enterprises had progressed--in apparel, office equipment, semiconductors and electronic parts, and audio and video equipment--imports continued to increase. Behind such changes in the trade structure, we can find the influence of the yen's sharp rise in value following the Plaza Accord of 1985. The yen's appreciation lowered import prices (calculated on the basis of the yen) and weakened the ability of domestically manufactured goods to remain price-competitive. In order to respond to the yen's sharp rise and deal with trade problems, however, Japanese enterprises aggressively engaged in foreign direct investments and succeeded in transferring their production bases overseas. As a result, re-imported products--for the most part mass market consumer products--penetrated the domestic market while exports, in order to keep the work force employed at home, centered on high value added items that could not be produced at overseas plants, thus creating specialization, or an international division of labor, in the production of manufactured goods. In the future, too, domestic and foreign economic trends permitting, Japanese enterprises are expected to expand their overseas operations even further, just as they have since the latter half of the 1980's, as long as yen continues its upward climb. Table 4. Changes in Japan's Principal Manufactured Imports (Unit: $100 million) 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 Total exported 528 660 918 1,061 1,180 1,203 1,170 amount Consumer, capital goods Apparel 29 46 67 89 87 93 112 Office equipment 17 22 33 44 52 56 60 Semiconductors, 12 15 23 29 33 39 40 electronic parts Aircraft 18 17 20 17 32 32 32 Audio, video 4 8 14 19 18 22 25 equipment Luxury items Automobiles 11 21 32 42 64 54 52 Gold 70 35 41 35 36 26 20 Diamonds 9 14 21 22 25 21 18 Paintings 3 8 14 21 34 7 3 Steel, nonferrous metals Steel 18 25 46 51 46 55 38 Aluminum, 16 27 50 51 48 46 36 aluminum alloys Copper, copper 5 7 13 17 19 18 11 alloys Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics This article will first examine trends in Japanese foreign direct investments, the engine behind changes in Japan's trade structure, in three areas: North America, Europe and Asia. A larger share of all foreign direct investments during the latter half of the 1980's was going to Asia, reflecting the importance placed on this region in the corporate strategies of Japanese enterprises. While we can gather from their profits that Japanese-owned enterprises engaged in local production in Europe and the United States are having a hard time, operations in Asia are proceeding smoothly, comparatively speaking, and in the future, we can expect the relative importance of this region for Japanese enterprises to increase even further. Wide variations exist among different industries when it comes to local production. The picture, however, in terms of changes in trade structure due to foreign direct investments, when considered on an industry by industry basis (here, the automobile, consumer appliance and electronics, apparel, and steel industries will be considered), indicates that in each of these industries, manufacturers are exporting high value added products. On the other hand, the trend in imports is toward mass distribution consumer products. Thus, we can see that, in terms of exports and imports, an international division of labor, or "segregation of niche" [sumiwake] is developing. During the latter half of the 1980's, a large wave of foreign direct investments was developing, even on an international scale, (with investments going from advanced countries to other advanced countries and from advanced countries to developing nations), and as a result, there has been a shift in the world's trade structure, including Japan's, from vertical to horizontal trade. This shift can be understood in terms of changes in the index of intra-industry trade (ITT), an indicator of the degree to which horizontal (intra-industry) trade has developed. Not only has Asia, a region actively receiving direct investments from advanced nations, including Japan, seen a brisk, quickening of trade, close trading ties within the region are developing as domestic demand among Asian countries expands. Changes in Japan's trade structure and in its regional ties can also be seen from the perspective of Japan's international air cargo. II. Trends in Japanese Foreign Direct Investments 1. General Remarks From the end of the 1980's into the 1990's, foreign direct investments by Japanese enterprises have increased dramatically as companies have embarked on plans to transfer their domestic production bases overseas. This move has been in response to a downturn in the profitability of exports due to the yen's steep rise following the 1985 Plaza Accord and in response to voluntary export restrictions and worsening trade relations of the kind seen in anti-dumping suits (Table 5). ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Table 5. Changes in Japanese Foreign Direct Investments (Manufacturing In-| |dustry) (Unit: $100 million; percent) | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Fiscal year |World total |North America |Europe |Asia | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |1986 |38.6 (100) |22.0 (58) |3.7 (10) |8.0 (21) | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |1987 |78.3 (100) |48.5 (62) |8.5 (11) |16.8 (21) | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |1988 |138.1 (100) |91.9 (67) |15.5 (11) |23.7 (17) | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------- |1989 |162.8 (100) |95.8 (59) |30.9 (19) |32.2 (20) | ----------------------------