ties are often raised by companies in the country where those facilities are located and the connection between direct investments from Japan and the further development of local production becomes weaker.) In considering regional changes in Japan's foreign direct investments, we see that North America was Japan's principal target for investors, their reasons for investing in this region being to maintain and expand their market shares and to develop new markets; additionally, investors have been motivated by the desire to avoid trade problems. As can be seen in responses to the questionnaire given to Japanese enterprises on their reasons for branching out overseas (Table 6), oftentimes the motive, in the case of North America and Europe was to cope with trade restrictions set up by their trading partners. In 1988, 67 percent of [Japan's] foreign direct investments went to North America, but that figure has since dropped, falling to 42 percent in 1992. Among the reasons for this decline are the business slump in the United States and the fact that Japanese enterprises have just finished a round of large-scale production projects (Table 7). Europe's share of foreign direct investments, about 10 percent, was relatively low until 1988, but with the economic unification of the European Community (EC) slated for 1992, Japanese-owned enterprises, believing they should try to gain "insider status," hurriedly began to move into the region from the latter half of the 1980's, bringing EC's share of Japanese investments to 30 percent in 1990. Because of the business slump in Europe, particularly in England, which receives from one-third to one-fourth of the direct investments from Japan (Table 7), less money is being invested in the area, and Europe's share dropped to 21 percent in 1992. Ideally, there are two routes companies can take when moving into advanced market countries (i.e., North America and Europe): they can either set up their own production bases there through foreign direct investments (local production) or they can base their production on tie-ups with [local] enterprises (establish mutually complementary production relationships, OEM [original equipment manufacturer] tie-ups, technical tie-ups, or joint development). In recent years, rather than through foreign direct investments, more weight has been given to the latter route; namely, cooperative dealings between companies and joint technical development based on strategic tie-ups with foreign enterprises. As a result, Japanese companies have been placing less importance on foreign direct investments. Asia, with its abundance of cheap labor, on the other hand, has been designated a production base for Japanese-owned enterprises and since 1988, has steadily been receiving a larger share of Japan's foreign direct investments. In 1992, this share reached an all time high of 31 percent. But even within the same region, interest has been shifting since 1990 from ASEAN [Association of Southeast Asian Nation] member countries to China. Thus, it seems that in recent years, Japan's foreign direct investments have been shifting from North America and Europe to Asia. Table 6. Main Reasons for Foreign Direct Investments (multiple choice) (Unit: percent) Reason North EC NIE's ASEAN China America Expand, maintain 50.0 50.0 39.2 43.3 35.9 local market share Develop new 17.0 26.1 15.2 14.4 34.4 markets Cope with trade 15.0 12.5 0.0 2.9 3.1 restrictions Secure cheap 2.0 2.3 2.5 26.0 10.9 labor Secure stable 5.0 1.1 6.3 8.7 10.9 source of resources, raw materials Demands of 1.0 0.0 0.0 4.8 15.6 trading partner Preferential tax 2.0 2.3 0.0 3.8 1.6 cuts in trading country Avoid exchange 1.0 3.4 1.3 3.0 4.7 rate risks Part of 8.0 10.2 12.7 15.4 4.7 company's division of labor policy Spread 11.0 9.1 8.9 17.3 6.3 production bases overseas Secure talented 2.0 1.1 1.3 0.0 1.6 overseas researchers Develop products 8.0 12.5 1.3 1.9 3.1 meeting local market needs Shift existing 1.0 2.3 1.3 1.0 4.7