2.5 3.6 5.7 parts Growth rate -25.6 13.1 64.1 46.5 49.2 45.8 59.1 Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics With the political situation turning more stable and the government adopting a policy of openness and reform, Japanese enterprises have also been establishing production bases since 1990 in China, where labor costs are extremely low. Within China, durable consumer goods like refrigerators, washing machines and television sets--consumer products that are becoming part of the necessities of daily life--are coming into general use, and manufacturers are anticipating growth in the durable consumer market and products like air conditioners and audio-video equipment along with a rise in China's standard of living. 3. Apparel Industry The apparel industry is labor-intensive, and because it became less profitable to export apparel from Japan when the yen gained strength following the Plaza Accord, Japanese enterprises have gone about aggressively setting up local production facilities in Asia in order to utilize the region's relatively cheap labor (Table 18). China, where labor costs are especially cheap, has emerged as an important production base for mass market apparel. At the present time, however, technical standards for cloth and dying and quality control are still inadequate, and quality control is being handled in Japan. Cut cloth is then exported and sewn and assembled locally. Thus, there has developed a form of specialization or division of labor. Statistical data clearly show changes of this kind with regard to Japan's import partners. Until 1990, Korea was the apparel industries number one importer; then, from 1991, when wages went up and Korea lost its price-competitiveness, China assumed that head position (Table 19). While inexpensive (mass market) apparel is being imported from Asia, domestic apparel makers are manufacturing expensive items (high value added items whose selling point is superior design), which cannot be produced overseas, and are thus creating a division of labor in terms of imported items and domestically manufactured items. Table 18. Changes by Region in Foreign Direct Investments by Textile Industry (Unit: $100 million, no. of investments) 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 Total 0.6 2.1 3.2 5.3 8.0 6.2 4.3 dollar (45) (94) (146) (174) (200) (242) (311) amount North 0.2 1.3 1.0 (9) 1.6 1.1 2.3 0.7 (9) America (5) (18) (24) (17) (16) Europe 0.2 0.4 0.6 1.9 3.8 1.6 1.1 (17) (25) (25) (39) (45) (44) (47) Asia 0.2 0.3 1.5 1.9 3.0 2.2 2.3 (18) (45) (106) (112) (136) (179) (252) Source: Ministry of Finance (Monthly Statistical Report, etc.) Note: Figures in parentheses ( ) indicate number of investments Table 19. Changes in Apparel Imports (Unit: $100 million, percent change) 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 Total 28.5 46.5 67.0 89.4 87.0 93.4 111.7 dollar amount Growth 43.0 63.0 44.1 33.4 -2.7 7.3 19.6 rate China 5.6 8.3 14.5 22.1 23.9 32.3 48.6 Growth 20.8 50.0 73.8 52.4 8.2 35.4 50.2 rate Korea 9.8 17.6 26.5 31.4 24.5 23.3 21.7 Growth 58.1 79.3 50.7 18.7 -22.1 -5.0 -6.7 rate Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics 4. Steel Industry In addition to being one of the items subject to managed trade and to voluntary export restrictions, steel exports have dropped in volume (quantitatively) because they have become less price-competitive following the yen's appreciation after the Plaza Accord. However, the total dollar amount of steel exports has shown very little change, and proportionally more high value added items are being exported Table 20). Specifically, while high value added export items like surface treated steel sheeting (for use in auto bodies and treated to prevent corrosion) and special steel materials exports are increasing, the export of low value added products like hot rolled steel and bar iron is decreasing (Table 21). On the other hand, the trend seems to be toward a steady growth in imports from Taiwan and Korea, both in terms of quantitative and cash volume. (In 1992, however, there was a large drop in import volume because the domestic economy was entering an adjustment phase.) Types of steel materials being imported are for the most part low value added products like pig iron, semi-finished steel ingot products and hot rolled steel sheets (Table 22). A comparison of unit prices for imports and exports indicates that the latter is about twice that for imports, indicating the development of a "segregation of niche" (Table 20). In the United States, where the steel industry's primary overseas expansion has occurred, Japanese steel makers, responding to concerns about U.S.-Japan trade friction, began by providing U.S. manufacturers with technical assistance and, at present, are undertaking production in the form of mergers with U.S. steel manufacturers. This does not mean, however, that re-imported steel from the United States has increased; rather products manufactured in the United States are being sold on the local market. Japanese steel makers have also provided technical cooperation to developing nations, and as the technical level in those countries improves, inexpensive steel will probably start being exported to Japan in earnest (Table 23.) [passage omitted] Table 20. Changes in Unit Price, Volume of Steel Exports, Imports (Unit: $100 million; 10,000 metric ton; dollar/metric ton) 1980 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 Exports Dollar 154.5 127.1 126.1 153.2 147.9 125.1 136.1 133.3 amount Tonnage 2,986 2,993 2,536 2,336 1,991 1,674 1,780 1,875 Unit 517.6 424.5 497.3 656.0 742.8 747.5 764.9 711.1 price Imports Dollar 8.9 17.6 24.8 46.3 50.7 45.8 55.0 37.9 amount Tonnage 243 525 747 1,114 1,086 1,170 1,385 888 Unit 368.3 335.7 332.7 415.3 466.7 391.8 397.4 426.3 price Source: Ministry of Finance trade statistics Table 21. Changes in Categories of Exported Steel Products as a Percentage of All Steel Exports (Unit: percent of all steel exports) 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 All categories 100.0 100.0 100.0 100.0 100.0 100.0 