g in high value added, high tech products through the development of innovative technology. While the furthering of local production by Japanese enterprises is inescapable, the course will not necessarily be smooth sailing. It holds out many difficulties, not only in terms of production and production management technology but also in the "soft" sciences of labor and business management. In North America and Europe, where Japanese enterprises were initially motivated to move primarily in order to avoid trade problems, companies are having a tough time in terms of profits, and the situation and future direction of local production there warrants careful attention. In Asia, on the other hand, companies were motivate by the sound economic desire to seek cheap labor and are seeing satisfactory profits. At present, North America remains the most important region for Japan in terms of local production; but it seems only natural that, with the growing, future potential of the Asian market, Japanese enterprises will be embarking on overseas corporate strategies that stress the importance of Asia. Designating Asia as a production base not only means a production base for exports but also signifies Asia's transformation into a production base targeting local sales as regional demand expands.
